 Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Clayton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of numerous places, in Yorkshire, Lancashire, Staffordshire, and Sussex, named Clayton, from Old English <i>clǣg</i> ‘clay’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘enclosure, settlement’."],"variants":[{"name":"Cleeton","meanings":["English (Shropshire and Worcestershire): variant of   Clayton  ."]},{"name":"Cleaton","meanings":["English (Montgomeryshire): variant of   Clayton  ."]}]},{"name":"Maud","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval vernacular form of   Matilda .  This form was characteristically Low German (i.e. including medieval Dutch and Flemish). The wife of  William the Conqueror , who bore this name, was the daughter of  Baldwin , Count of Flanders. In Flemish and Dutch the letter <i>-t-</i> was generally lost when it occurred between vowels, giving forms such as <i>Ma(h)auld</i>. <i>Maud</i> or <i>Matilda</i> was also the name of the daughter (  1102–67 ) of  Henry I  of England; she was married early in life to the Holy Roman Emperor  Henry V , and later disputed the throne of England with her cousin  Stephen . In  1128  she married  Geoffrey , Count of Anjou. A medieval chronicler commented, ‘she was a good woman, but she had little bliss with him’. The name <i>Maud</i> became quite common in England in the 19th century, when its popularity was influenced in part by  Tennyson's  poem Maud, published in  1855 , but has not been much used since the early decades of the 20th century."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Maud de Clayton was born in 1230, in Clayton, Lancashire, England. She had at least 2 sons with Sir Robert de Byron. She died after 1248, in England."},"et":{"1230–after 1248":"1230–pärast 1248","1210–1280":"1210–1280","1237–1280":"1237–1280","1254–Male":"1254–Surnud","1230–1248":"1230–1248","after 1248":"pärast 1248","1248":"1248","1237":"1237","Cir 1237":"1237","1254":"1254","1210":"1210","1230":"1230","1280":"1280","Clayton, Lancashire, England":"Clayton, Lancashire, England","Melling, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom":"Melling, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England"},"fi":{"1230–after 1248":"1230–1248 jälkeen","1210–1280":"1210–1280","1237–1280":"1237–1280","1254–Male":"1254–Kuollut","1230–1248":"1230–1248","after 1248":"1248 jälkeen","1248":"1248","1237":"1237","Cir 1237":"1237","1254":"1254","1210":"1210","1230":"1230","1280":"1280","Clayton, Lancashire, England":"Clayton, Lancashire, England","Melling, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom":"Melling, Lancashire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","England":"England"},"fr":{"1230–after 1248":"1230–après 1248","1210–1280":"1210–1280","1237–1280":"1237–1280","1254–Male":"1254–Décédé","1230–1248":"1230–1248","after 1248":"après 1248","1248":"1248","1237":"1237","Cir 1237":"1237","1254":"1254","1210":"1210","1230":"1230","1280":"1280","Clayton, Lancashire, England":"Clayton, Lancashire, Angleterre","Melling, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom":"Melling, Lancashire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","England":"Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Maud de Clayton est née en 1230, à Clayton, Lancashire, Angleterre. Elle a eu au moins 2 fils avec Sir Robert de Byron. Elle est décédée après 1248, à Angleterre."},"de":{"1230–after 1248":"1230–nach 1248","1210–1280":"1210–1280","1237–1280":"1237–1280","1254–Male":"1254–Ver